Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence: Mathematical Foundations, Architecture, and Theoretical Certification for Robust Robotic Interaction

Author:
Ouadi Maakoul

version 2.02

---

Abstract

Despite remarkable progress in robotic perception and planning, contemporary robots remain fundamentally brittle when interacting with the physical world. The core failure mode—articulated in Problem ACT-ROBOT-2026-002—is motor instability under contact uncertainty: objects slip, delicate materials fracture, and performance collapses under minor environmental variations. This failure stems not from a lack of visual acuity but from a theoretical gap: the translation of intent into stable, adaptive physical action in the presence of discontinuous contact dynamics.

This thesis addresses this gap by formulating Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI) , a principled mathematical framework and control architecture designed to certify robust, real-time interaction. We abandon the traditional smooth-dynamics assumption and model robot–environment coupling as a hybrid differential inclusion with Filippov regularization, explicitly accounting for the Signorini–Coulomb conditions of rigid contact and friction.

The proposed ASI architecture is a two-timescale hybrid controller. At the fast timescale (1 kHz), a Quadratic Program (QP) projects a learned nominal policy onto a safe set defined by Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) and Control Barrier Functions (CBFs), ensuring safety and stability. At the slow timescale (10–100 Hz), online meta-learning updates a latent environment model and refines a Lipschitz-regularized residual policy, enabling rapid adaptation to varying object mass, friction, and disturbance profiles.

The core contribution of this thesis is theoretical certification. We prove four foundational theorems that guarantee the system's performance:

1. Input-to-State Stability (ISS) in the presence of bounded disturbances and hybrid contact transitions.
2. Bounded Dynamic Regret for the online adaptation process, demonstrating sublinear cumulative loss even under non-stationary task distributions.
3. PAC-Bayes Generalization Bound that quantifies and certifies the reduction of the simulation-to-reality transfer gap.
4. Exponential Contraction of the closed-loop dynamics with learned residuals, ensuring robust convergence to desired trajectories.

No physical experiments are conducted. Instead, this work provides a complete mathematical blueprint and a set of verifiable design principles. The theorems serve as a priori certificates that a system constructed according to the ASI framework can, in principle, overcome the sensorimotor translation gap and achieve robust, safe, and adaptive interaction in unstructured real-world environments.

Keywords: Sensorimotor Control, Hybrid Dynamical Systems, Meta-Reinforcement Learning, Sim-to-Real Transfer, Control Barrier Functions, Input-to-State Stability, Robotic Manipulation.

