Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 The Sensorimotor Translation Gap

The last decade has witnessed an unprecedented acceleration in robotic perception. Deep neural networks can now segment scenes, recognize objects under severe occlusion, and estimate six-degree-of-freedom poses with accuracy rivaling human vision. Yet, the promise of ubiquitous, capable robots operating alongside humans in homes, hospitals, and factories remains largely unfulfilled. The bottleneck is no longer seeing the world; it is acting upon it.

Consider a robot tasked with inserting a USB cable, flipping a delicate pancake, or handing a fragile glass of water to a human. In each scenario, the visual objective is clear, but the physical execution is fraught with uncertainty. The robot must regulate contact forces with millisecond precision, adapt to the unknown compliance of the object, and react instantaneously to slippage or unexpected collisions. In current practice, even state-of-the-art robotic systems frequently fail in these contact-rich tasks. They drop objects, apply excessive force, or exhibit unstable oscillations when faced with a surface that is slightly more slippery or rigid than anticipated.

This phenomenon is encapsulated in Problem ID: ACT-ROBOT-2026-002, which identifies the core challenge as the translation of intent into stable, adaptive physical action under uncertainty. The failure modes—motor instability, slip, breakage, and sim-to-real transfer breakdown—are symptoms of a deeper mathematical inadequacy in how we model and control physical interaction.

1.2 The Inadequacy of Smooth Control Paradigms

Traditional robotic control is dominated by two paradigms: classical model-based methods (e.g., PID control, impedance control, computed torque) and modern learning-based methods (e.g., Reinforcement Learning policies trained in simulation). Both share a common, often implicit, assumption: the system dynamics are sufficiently smooth.

A standard PID controller, defined by the law \tau = K_p(x_{\text{target}} - x) + K_d(\dot{x}_{\text{target}} - \dot{x}), assumes that the error dynamics are governed by a linear time-invariant (LTI) or mildly nonlinear system. This assumption breaks down catastrophically at the moment of contact. When a robot end-effector transitions from free space to touching a rigid table, the effective inertia and damping of the system change instantaneously. The force-velocity relationship is no longer differentiable; it is governed by the Signorini–Coulomb conditions of unilateral constraint and friction cone nonlinearity. In this regime, a PID controller tuned for free motion will either bounce off the surface (instability) or exert dangerously high forces (safety violation).

Similarly, Reinforcement Learning (RL) policies, typically modeled as Markov Decision Processes (MDPs) with stationary transition probabilities P(s'|s,a), struggle to generalize. A policy trained to grasp a specific mug in simulation with a friction coefficient \mu_{\text{sim}} will fail when encountering a real mug with a slightly different surface texture (\mu_{\text{real}} \neq \mu_{\text{sim}}). The underlying transition dynamics have shifted, and the policy, being a static mapping, has no mechanism to detect or compensate for this shift online. Domain randomization attempts to mitigate this by training on a wide distribution of parameters, but it does not solve the problem of online adaptation to specific, unseen instances.

1.3 Research Gap and Proposed Approach

Research Gap Statement: There exists no unified theoretical framework and corresponding control architecture that provides certified guarantees for real-time adaptive sensorimotor intelligence in the face of discontinuous contact dynamics and non-stationary environmental parameters.

This thesis addresses this gap by proposing Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI) . We argue that robust physical interaction requires a hybrid systems perspective and a two-timescale control strategy. Specifically, we must:

1. Model the system correctly: Acknowledge contact as a hybrid dynamical system with state-dependent switching, not a smooth perturbation.
2. Separate concerns in time: Delegate high-frequency safety and stability to a reactive, optimization-based controller, while allowing a slower learning process to adapt the internal model of the environment.
3. Provide certificates, not just heuristics: Derive formal guarantees of stability, regret, generalization, and contraction that hold even under the hybrid dynamics model.

1.4 Thesis Contributions and Theoretical Scope

This is a theoretical thesis. It does not present new hardware, novel simulation environments, or empirical benchmarking results. The contributions are entirely mathematical and architectural. The specific contributions are:

1. A Formal Hybrid Dynamical Model (Section 3.2): A rigorous formulation of robot–environment interaction using differential inclusions and Filippov regularization, which serves as the analytical foundation for all subsequent analysis.
2. The ASI Control Architecture (Section 3.3): A precise definition of a two-timescale, hierarchical controller that integrates:
   · A fast Safety-Filtered QP using CLF and CBF constraints.
   · A Lipschitz-regularized Residual Policy for unmodeled dynamics.
   · An Online Meta-Adaptation Law with decaying step-size for non-stationary environment tracking.
3. Four Foundational Theorems with Proof Sketches (Section 3.4 and Appendix A):
   · Theorem 3.1 (ISS): Proving that the closed-loop system remains bounded-input bounded-state stable despite hybrid contact disturbances.
   · Theorem 3.2 (Dynamic Regret): Bounding the cumulative performance loss of the online learner under task drift.
   · Theorem 3.3 (PAC-Bayes): Certifying the expected real-world performance based on simulation training and online adaptation.
   · Theorem 3.4 (Contraction): Demonstrating exponential convergence of trajectories under the learned residual policy.
4. Design Principles (Section 3.5): Translating the mathematical certificates into concrete, verifiable constraints on the neural network architecture and optimization hyperparameters.

The overarching contribution is a certification framework that shifts the validation of robotic interaction from empirical trial-and-error to a priori mathematical guarantee.

1.5 Thesis Organization

The remainder of this thesis is structured as follows:

· Chapter 2: Background and Related Work provides a comprehensive review of the literature. We survey classical robotic control, reinforcement learning for manipulation, hybrid systems theory, sim-to-real transfer techniques, and meta-learning. We situate our work relative to these fields and highlight the specific theoretical gaps that motivate ASI.
· Chapter 3: Mathematical Foundations of Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence constitutes the core of the thesis. It presents the formal dynamical model, the ASI architecture in full mathematical detail, and the four certification theorems with their proof sketches.
· Chapter 4: Algorithmic Instantiation and Design Verification bridges the gap between theory and implementation. It outlines how the abstract mathematical entities can be realized in a practical neural control system and proposes verifiable metrics to ensure adherence to theoretical assumptions.
· Chapter 5: Discussion and Future Work reflects on the implications of the ASI framework, its limitations, and avenues for future theoretical extensions (e.g., stochastic contraction, higher-order CBFs, and integration with large language model planners).
· Chapter 6: Conclusion summarizes the thesis and reaffirms the importance of certified, adaptive control for the future of embodied AI.

