Chapter 2: Background and Related Work

This chapter establishes the academic context for Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI). We survey the foundational fields that inform our approach and identify the specific theoretical shortcomings that ASI is designed to overcome. The review is organized into four thematic pillars: (2.1) Classical and Modern Robotic Control, (2.2) Learning for Manipulation and Contact, (2.3) Hybrid Systems and Safety-Critical Control, and (2.4) Meta-Learning and Domain Adaptation. The chapter concludes with a synthesis that defines the precise research gap addressed in Chapter 3.

2.1 Classical and Modern Robotic Control

2.1.1 Model-Based Control and Its Limitations

The bedrock of robotic manipulation is the Lagrangian formulation of rigid-body dynamics:

M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = \tau + \tau_{\text{ext}}

Classical control strategies exploit the structure of this equation. Computed Torque Control (Craig, 1986) uses a model of M, C, and g to exactly cancel the nonlinearities, reducing the system to a double integrator \ddot{q} = u. Impedance Control (Hogan, 1985) and Admittance Control regulate the dynamic relationship between force and motion, allowing robots to exhibit compliant behavior.

However, these methods are model-dependent. They require precise knowledge of kinematic and inertial parameters, which may change when the robot grasps an object of unknown mass. More critically, they assume continuous contact dynamics. The transition from free space to rigid constraint is treated as a disturbance to be rejected rather than a fundamental change in the system's degrees of freedom. As noted by Brogliato (2016) and others, standard impedance control can exhibit instability during the impact phase of contact.

2.1.2 Adaptive Control and System Identification

To address parametric uncertainty, Adaptive Control (Slotine & Li, 1991) was developed. These methods estimate unknown parameters (e.g., mass, link length) online using recursive least squares or gradient descent and update the control law accordingly. The Slotine-Li adaptive controller provides a Lyapunov-based proof of trajectory tracking convergence despite constant unknown parameters.

Limitations in Context: Standard adaptive control assumes the parameters are constant or slowly varying and that the structure of the dynamics is known. In unstructured manipulation, the parameters (friction coefficient, object geometry) can change abruptly upon contact with a new surface. Furthermore, these methods cannot learn to compensate for unmodeled phenomena like complex friction hysteresis or soft-body deformation from first principles.

2.2 Learning for Manipulation and Contact

2.2.1 Reinforcement Learning (RL) in Robotics

The advent of deep reinforcement learning has enabled robots to learn complex motor skills directly from experience or simulation (Kober et al., 2013; Levine et al., 2018). Policies \pi_\theta(a|s) are trained to maximize cumulative reward. Model-free RL algorithms (e.g., PPO, SAC) have demonstrated impressive results in dexterous manipulation, quadrupedal locomotion, and in-hand object reorientation (OpenAI et al., 2019).

Limitations in Context (ACT-ROBOT-2026-002):

· Sample Inefficiency: Training contact-rich tasks from scratch in the real world is prohibitively time-consuming and dangerous.
· Sim-to-Real Transfer Gap: Policies trained exclusively in simulation suffer from a reality gap. The visual textures, actuator dynamics, and contact physics differ between the simulator and reality. While domain randomization (Tobin et al., 2017) improves robustness by training over a distribution of simulator parameters, it does not eliminate the gap; it merely produces a policy that is conservatively average across the distribution, often sacrificing peak performance for robustness.
· Static Policy Assumption: Most deployed RL policies are frozen after training. They do not adapt online when they encounter an out-of-distribution environment. This violates the requirement for real-time adaptation outlined in the problem statement.

2.2.2 Learning Residuals and Hybrid Architectures

A promising direction to combine the reliability of model-based control with the flexibility of learning is the residual policy approach (Johannink et al., 2019). Here, the control torque is decomposed as \tau = \tau_{\text{model-based}} + \pi_\theta^{\text{res}}(\text{state}). The learned component compensates for unmodeled dynamics or disturbances. This is a direct precursor to our ASI formulation. Recent work has also explored Diffusion Policies (Chi et al., 2023) for expressing multimodal action distributions, which is crucial for tasks like pushing or insertion where multiple valid contact strategies exist.

Limitations in Context: While effective, these methods lack formal stability guarantees when the residual policy is a deep neural network. Without constraints, a poorly initialized or over-confident residual can destabilize an otherwise stable nominal controller. Our ASI framework addresses this by explicitly bounding the Lipschitz constant of the residual and filtering the combined action through a safety-critical QP.

2.3 Hybrid Systems and Safety-Critical Control

2.3.1 Hybrid Dynamical Systems and Filippov Solutions

The mathematics of contact requires moving beyond smooth ordinary differential equations. Hybrid Dynamical Systems theory (Goebel et al., 2012) provides the formalism for systems with both continuous flows and discrete jumps. The transition from non-contact to contact is a state-dependent switching event.

When the vector field is discontinuous, classical solutions may not exist. Filippov's method (Filippov, 1988) extends the notion of a solution by replacing the discontinuous differential equation \dot{x} = f(x) with a differential inclusion \dot{x} \in \mathbf{F}(x), where \mathbf{F}(x) is the convex hull of the limiting vector fields at the discontinuity. This is the rigorous mathematical language required to analyze the stability of robots making and breaking contact—a core element of our model. Brogliato (2016) and the survey by Stewart (2000) confirm that this framework, combined with complementarity formulations (NCP), is the standard for simulating and analyzing rigid-body contact with friction.

2.3.2 Control Barrier Functions (CBFs) and Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs)

Control Barrier Functions (CBFs) (Ames et al., 2017; 2019) provide a powerful tool for ensuring safety (i.e., forward invariance of a safe set) in continuous control systems. Given a set \mathcal{C} = \{x \mid h(x) \geq 0\}, a function h is a CBF if there exists a control input such that \dot{h}(x, u) + \kappa h(x) \geq 0.

Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) provide a dual tool for ensuring stability (convergence to a goal). By combining CLFs and CBFs into a single Quadratic Program (QP) (Ames & Powell, 2013), one can synthesize a controller that minimally modifies a nominal input to satisfy both safety and stability constraints.

Limitations in Context: The standard CLF-CBF-QP framework assumes an accurate model to compute \dot{h} and \dot{V}. In the presence of significant model error (the very problem we face in contact-rich tasks), the QP may become infeasible or the safety guarantees may be violated. Robust CBFs (Garg et al., 2024) have been proposed to handle bounded disturbances. Our ASI framework integrates this robustness concept with a learned residual, providing the first ISS guarantee for a CBF-protected system that uses online meta-learning. The work of Heemels et al. (2008) on ISS for discontinuous systems provides the essential mathematical bridge.

2.4 Meta-Learning and Domain Adaptation for Robotics

2.4.1 Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning (MAML)

The requirement to "learn new tasks dynamically" points toward Meta-Learning. MAML (Finn et al., 2017) is an algorithm for learning a model initialization \theta that can adapt to a new task with only a few gradient steps. In robotics, MAML has been used to enable rapid adaptation of locomotion policies to changes in terrain or payload (Nagabandi et al., 2019).

Limitations in Context: MAML is typically an offline meta-training algorithm. The inner loop adaptation happens during a dedicated adaptation phase, not continuously during task execution. Our ASI framework extends this to continuous online adaptation (the slow timescale), requiring a new analysis of dynamic regret to ensure the updates do not interfere with the fast stability loop. The regret analysis draws on the work of Fei et al. (2020) on non-stationary reinforcement learning.

2.4.2 PAC-Bayesian Generalization Bounds for Sim-to-Real

A rigorous understanding of the sim-to-real gap requires statistical learning theory. PAC-Bayes theory (McAllester, 1999) provides bounds on the generalization error of randomized classifiers. Recent work (Hsu et al., 2022) has applied PAC-Bayes to RL policies, bounding the difference between simulated and real-world returns based on the KL divergence between the training distribution P (augmented with domain randomization) and the posterior distribution over policies Q found during adaptation. Their bound explicitly accounts for the structural mismatch between simulation and reality, which we incorporate as the \Delta_{\text{dyn}} term in Theorem 3.3.

2.5 Synthesis and Research Gap

The literature contains separate, highly advanced components: robust CBFs for safety, meta-learning for fast adaptation, and PAC-Bayes for generalization analysis. However, no existing work unifies these components within a single mathematically certified framework for hybrid contact dynamics. The ASI architecture and its accompanying theorems, presented in the following chapter, provide this missing synthesis. We prove that by imposing a two-timescale structure and a Lipschitz constraint on the learned residual, we can simultaneously achieve:

· ISS (via CBF/CLF and Filippov analysis),
· Bounded Regret (via online meta-learning with decaying step-size),
· Certified Sim-to-Real Transfer (via PAC-Bayes with structural mismatch term).


Chapter 3: Mathematical Foundations of Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence

Problem ID: ACT-ROBOT-2026-002
Thesis Context: Foundations of Embodied Learning and Real-World Robotic Control

---

3.1 Introduction: The Sensorimotor Translation Gap

The deployment of autonomous robots in unstructured, human-centric environments exposes a critical failure mode absent from simulated benchmarks: motor instability under contact uncertainty. As articulated in Problem ACT-ROBOT-2026-002, robots consistently fail not because they cannot see the world, but because they cannot translate visual intent into stable, adaptive physical action. Objects slip, delicate structures break, and performance collapses under minor environmental variations.

The core mathematical challenge is the hybrid nature of contact. Standard control laws, whether classical PID (\tau = K_p e + K_d \dot{e}) or learned policies \pi_\theta(a|s) derived from Markov Decision Processes (MDPs), assume smooth transition dynamics. Reality is defined by discontinuous jumps in system impedance—the instantaneous transition from free-space motion to rigid, frictional constraint. This chapter establishes the mathematical framework that resolves this discontinuity.

We propose Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI) , a two-timescale hybrid control architecture that couples high-frequency safety-critical control with online meta-learning. The contribution of this chapter is theoretical: we provide a formal dynamical model, a precise architectural definition, and four foundational theorems with complete proof sketches that certify the system's stability, regret, generalization, and contraction properties. No empirical data is presented; this is the mathematical blueprint upon which all subsequent algorithmic development rests.

3.2 Formal Dynamical Model: Hybrid Systems and Contact Complementarity

To reason rigorously about physical interaction, we must abandon the fiction of smooth vector fields. We model the robot–environment system as a hybrid dynamical system with state-dependent switching.

Definition 3.1 (System State).
Let the state be x = (q, \dot{q}, \lambda) \in \mathcal{X} \subset \mathbb{R}^{2n+m}, where:

· q \in \mathbb{R}^n are generalized joint coordinates,
· \dot{q} \in \mathbb{R}^n are joint velocities,
· \lambda \in \mathbb{R}^m is the vector of contact forces (normal and tangential components).

Assumption 3.1 (Lagrangian Dynamics in Smooth Regime).
The robot obeys the standard manipulator equation away from impact events:

M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = \tau + J_c(q)^\top \lambda + d(t) \tag{3.1}

where M(q) \succ 0 is the inertia matrix, C(q,\dot{q}) is chosen to satisfy \dot{M} - 2C skew-symmetric, g(q) is gravity, J_c(q) is the contact Jacobian, \tau is control torque, and d(t) is a bounded exogenous disturbance with \|d(t)\| \leq D.

Assumption 3.2 (Contact Constraints and Filippov Regularization).
Contact forces \lambda are governed by the Signorini–Coulomb conditions. For the normal force \lambda_n:

\lambda_n \geq 0, \quad \phi_n(q) \geq 0, \quad \lambda_n \phi_n(q) = 0 \tag{3.2}

where \phi_n(q) is the signed distance to contact. For tangential force \lambda_t:

\lambda_t \in \mathcal{F}(\lambda_n), \quad \|\lambda_t\|_2 \leq \mu \lambda_n \tag{3.3}

where \mu is the friction coefficient and \mathcal{F} is the friction cone.

Because the vector field changes discontinuously at contact surfaces \Sigma = \{x \mid \phi_n(q)=0\}, we regularize using the Filippov convexification (Filippov, 1988). The dynamics are extended to the differential inclusion:

\dot{x} \in \mathbf{F}(x) = \text{co}\{f_i(x) \mid i \in I(x)\} \tag{3.4}

where \{f_i\} are the vector fields from all possible contact mode combinations (e.g., sliding left, sliding right, sticking, separation) and \text{co} denotes the closed convex hull. This guarantees the existence of Carathéodory solutions (Brogliato, 2016; Stewart, 2000).

Definition 3.2 (Observation Model).
The robot receives multimodal sensory input. We assume a pre-trained cross-modal encoder \phi_\omega mapping visual and force data to a latent state z_t \in \mathbb{R}^d:

z_t = \phi_\omega(o_t), \quad o_t = [v_t^\top, f_t^\top]^\top \tag{3.5}

with bounded encoding error \mathbb{E}[\|z_t - z_t^*\|^2] \leq \epsilon_{\text{enc}}. Furthermore, we assume the availability of tactile uncertainty sets \mathcal{C}_t satisfying conformal coverage: \mathbb{P}(z_t^* \in \mathcal{C}_t) \geq 1-\alpha for a chosen significance level \alpha.

3.3 The ASI Architecture: Two-Timescale Hybrid Stochastic Control

To satisfy the constraints of millisecond-level control loops (1 kHz) and the need for online adaptation to changing contact parameters (10–100 Hz), we propose a hierarchical, two-timescale architecture. The fast loop ensures safety and stability; the slow loop updates the model of the world.

Definition 3.3 (Composite Policy).
The control torque \tau is generated by the solution of a Quadratic Program (QP) that projects a nominal learned policy onto a safe set defined by Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) and Control Barrier Functions (CBFs):

\tau = \arg\min_{a \in \mathbb{R}^n, \delta \in \mathbb{R}} \frac{1}{2}\|a - \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}}(z)\|_2^2 + \frac{\rho}{2}\delta^2 \tag{3.6}

subject to:

\dot{V}(x, a) \leq -\alpha V(x) + \delta \quad \text{(CLF Stability Constraint)} \tag{3.7}

\dot{h}(x, a) + \kappa h(x) \geq 0 \quad \text{(CBF Safety Constraint)} \tag{3.8}

where:

· \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}} is a nominal neural policy (e.g., a diffusion policy or transformer-based sequence model) trained offline on a distribution of tasks.
· V(x) is a Lyapunov function certifying convergence to a target trajectory.
· h(x) is a Barrier function defining the safe set \mathcal{C} = \{x \mid h(x) \geq 0\} (e.g., avoiding excessive force \tau_{\text{break}}).
· \delta is a relaxation variable to maintain feasibility under model error.

Assumption 3.3 (Residual Compensation).
Even with the QP safety filter, the nominal policy \pi_\theta^{\text{nn}} may fail to account for unmodeled contact dynamics (e.g., the precise friction coefficient \mu or object mass m). We augment the policy with a Lipschitz-regularized residual policy \pi_\phi^{\text{res}} that operates on the latent state and an estimated environment parameter vector \hat{\theta}_t:

\tau_{\text{final}} = \tau_{\text{QP}} + \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}(z, \hat{\theta}_t) \tag{3.9}

with the constraint \|\partial \pi_\phi^{\text{res}} / \partial x\| \leq L to prevent destabilization of the fast loop.

Definition 3.4 (Online Meta-Adaptation Law).
The slow timescale updates the internal model \hat{\theta}_t and, if necessary, the policy parameters \theta via an online meta-learning gradient step. Given a replay buffer \mathcal{D}_t of recent interaction tuples, the update is:

\theta_{t+1} = \theta_t - \eta_t \left( \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}(\theta_t; \mathcal{D}_t) + \lambda \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\text{reg}}(\theta_t, \theta_0) \right) \tag{3.10}

with a decaying step-size \eta_t = \frac{D}{G\sqrt{t}} (where G is the gradient Lipschitz constant). The regularization term \mathcal{L}_{\text{reg}} is a proximity penalty to the meta-initialized parameters \theta_0, preventing catastrophic forgetting.

The meta-training objective that produced \theta_0 is the standard MAML bi-level optimization:

\min_\theta \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{T} \sim p(\mathcal{T})} \left[ \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}}\left( \theta - \alpha \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}}(\theta) \right) \right] \tag{3.11}

where the task distribution \mathcal{T} covers variations in object mass M_i, friction \mu_i, and disturbance profiles d_i.

3.4 Theoretical Guarantees: Core Theorems and Certification

We now present the mathematical certification of the ASI architecture. These theorems provide the guarantees required for deployment in safety-critical, uncertain environments.

3.4.1 Input-to-State Stability (ISS) under Contact Disturbances

Theorem 3.1 (ISS of Hybrid ASI).
Assume:

1. The base QP (Eq. 3.6–3.8) is feasible for all x \in \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}}.
2. The residual policy is L-Lipschitz in state.
3. The exogenous disturbance is bounded \|d(t)\| \leq D.
4. Timescale separation holds: the adaptation rate \eta_t \ll 1/\text{control bandwidth}.

Then the closed-loop ASI system is Input-to-State Stable (ISS) with respect to d(t). Specifically, there exist a class \mathcal{KL} function \beta and a class \mathcal{K}_\infty function \gamma such that:

\|x(t)\| \leq \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma(D) \tag{3.12}

Proof Sketch.
Define a composite Lyapunov function candidate V_c(x, \theta) = V_{\text{CLF}}(x) + \frac{\mu}{2}\|\theta - \theta^*\|^2, where V_{\text{CLF}} is the Lyapunov function from the QP constraint and \theta^* is a local optimum of the adaptation loss. Using the Filippov calculus for hybrid inclusions (Heemels et al., 2008), we evaluate the Lie derivative \dot{V}_c along the regularized dynamics.

From the QP constraint (3.7) and the skew-symmetry of \dot{M} - 2C, we have:

\dot{V}_{\text{CLF}} \leq -\alpha V_{\text{CLF}} + \gamma_1 \|d(t)\| + \gamma_2 \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\|

The Lipschitz bound on the residual and the slow variation of \theta (due to timescale separation) imply that the disturbance from the residual is bounded and can be absorbed into the \gamma(D) term. Applying the comparison lemma for differential inclusions (Filippov, 1988, Thm. 8.1) and the ISS results for discontinuous systems (Heemels et al., 2008, Thm. 1) yields the ISS bound. The cross-term from the parameter error is bounded via Young's inequality and the choice of sufficiently small \mu. \square

3.4.2 Dynamic Regret of Online Adaptation

Theorem 3.2 (Dynamic Regret Bound).
Assume the online loss \ell_t(\theta) is convex and G-Lipschitz on a compact set \Theta. Assume the task drift is bounded: \|\nabla\ell_t - \nabla\ell_{t-1}\| \leq \sigma. Using decaying step size \eta_t = \frac{D}{G\sqrt{t}}, the dynamic regret satisfies:

R_T^{\text{dyn}} = \sum_{t=1}^T \ell_t(\theta_t) - \min_{\theta \in \Theta} \sum_{t=1}^T \ell_t(\theta) \leq \mathcal{O}\left( D G \sqrt{T} + \sigma T \right) \tag{3.13}

Proof Sketch.
The proof decomposes the dynamic regret into a static regret term (minimizing over a fixed comparator sequence) and a path-length penalty \sum \|\theta_{t}^* - \theta_{t-1}^*\|. Standard online gradient descent analysis (Zinkevich, 2003) bounds the static regret by O(\sqrt{T}). The meta-initialization ensures the diameter D of the search space is small relative to random initialization. The term \sigma T accounts for the non-stationarity of the environment (e.g., changing friction due to wear). This matches the regime-dependent analysis of Fei et al. (2020) for non-stationary MDPs. The decaying step size and gradient clipping ensure the bound holds. \square

3.4.3 PAC-Bayes Certification for Sim-to-Real Transfer

Theorem 3.3 (Sim2Real Generalization Gap).
Let P be the prior distribution over dynamics parameters induced by simulation domain randomization. Let Q be the posterior distribution after online adaptation. Let the total variation mismatch between simulation and real dynamics be bounded by \Delta_{\text{dyn}} = \sup \|P_{\text{real}} - P_{\text{sim}}\|_{\text{TV}}. Then, with probability at least 1-\delta over the real-world samples:

\mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[R_{\text{real}}(\theta)] \leq \mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[R_{\text{sim}}(\theta)] + \sqrt{\frac{D_{\text{KL}}(Q \| P) + \log(1/\delta)}{2N}} + C \Delta_{\text{dyn}} \tag{3.14}

Proof Sketch.
This follows from the PAC-Bayes bound for control policies as presented by Hsu et al. (2022). The KL divergence D_{\text{KL}}(Q \| P) quantifies the information gained during online adaptation. Because P was constructed via heavy domain randomization, this divergence is naturally small (the prior covers the real distribution). The term C \Delta_{\text{dyn}} accounts for the irreducible physical discrepancy that cannot be captured by any parametric model (e.g., unmodeled flex in the links). Applying the Donsker-Varadhan variational formula and optimizing the bound yields the result. \square

3.4.4 Exponential Contraction with Learned Residuals

Theorem 3.4 (Contraction under Lipschitz Residual).
Assume the nominal closed-loop system (QP with perfect model) is contracting in a Riemannian metric M(x) \succ 0 with rate \lambda > 0. If the Lipschitz constant L of the residual policy satisfies L < \lambda, then the augmented system contracts exponentially with rate \lambda - L:

\|x(t) - y(t)\|_M \leq e^{-(\lambda - L)t} \|x(0) - y(0)\|_M \tag{3.15}

for any two trajectories x(t), y(t).

Proof Sketch.
Consider the variational dynamics of the displacement \delta x = x - y. The presence of the residual policy modifies the Jacobian: \delta\dot{x} = (A(x) + B(x)\frac{\partial \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}}{\partial x}) \delta x. The matrix measure \mu_{M}(\cdot) of this Jacobian satisfies (Tsukamoto et al., 2021):

\mu_{M}\left(A + B\frac{\partial \pi}{\partial x}\right) \leq \mu_{M}(A) + \|B\| \left\|\frac{\partial \pi}{\partial x}\right\| \leq -\lambda + L

Integrating the bound on \frac{d}{dt}\|\delta x\|_M yields the exponential decay. The Lipschitz constraint is enforced via spectral normalization (Miyato et al., 2018), and its value can be verified via power iteration (Abuduweili et al., 2024). \square

