The ASI framework provides a rigorous mathematical foundation for robust robotic interaction. Its limitations are clearly defined, and the extensions proposed offer a rich research agenda. By providing both the certification theorems and the engineering blueprint, this thesis aims to accelerate the transition from brittle, simulation-bound robots to adaptive, real-world capable embodied agents. The work of Heemels et al. (2008) on hybrid ISS, Fei et al. (2020) on dynamic regret, Hsu et al. (2022) on PAC-Bayes sim-to-real, and Tsukamoto et al. (2021) on contraction theory collectively form the theoretical bedrock upon which ASI is built. The next step is to erect the physical structure.

Chapter 6: Conclusion

6.1 Recapitulation of the Certification Framework

This thesis began with a clinically precise diagnosis: Problem ACT-ROBOT-2026-002. Contemporary robots, despite remarkable perceptual abilities, fail catastrophically when translating intent into physical action under uncertainty. Objects slip, delicate materials break, and performance collapses with minor environmental changes. The root cause is not sensory but theoretical: we lack a control framework that provides certified guarantees in the face of discontinuous contact dynamics and non-stationary environmental parameters.

To address this gap, we have developed Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI) —a rigorous mathematical framework and hierarchical control architecture. The contributions of this thesis are entirely theoretical and architectural:

1. Formal Hybrid Dynamical Model (Chapter 3): We modeled robot–environment interaction as a Filippov differential inclusion, explicitly accounting for the Signorini–Coulomb conditions of rigid contact. This formulation correctly captures the discontinuous nature of contact forces and provides the analytical foundation for all subsequent certification.
2. Two-Timescale ASI Architecture (Chapter 3): We defined a hierarchical controller that decouples fast safety-critical control (1 kHz) from slow environment adaptation (10–100 Hz). The architecture comprises:
   · A Safety Filter QP that projects a learned nominal policy onto a feasible set defined by Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) and Control Barrier Functions (CBFs).
   · A Lipschitz-Regularized Residual Policy that compensates for unmodeled contact dynamics.
