The problem of robust physical interaction is not solved by this thesis—it is merely formalized and certified. The path forward requires the collective effort of control theorists, machine learning researchers, and roboticists to implement, validate, and extend the ASI framework. We have provided the mathematical scaffolding; the next step is to erect the physical structure.

As robots move from the sterile confines of laboratories and factories into the messy, unpredictable real world, the demand for certified adaptive control will only intensify. Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence is a step toward that future: a future where robots do not merely see the world, but can safely and adaptively touch it.

