A.1 Proof of Theorem 3.1 (Input-to-State Stability of Hybrid ASI)

Theorem 3.1 (Restated). Assume: (i) The QP (Eq. 3.6–3.8) is feasible for all x \in \mathcal{X}_{\text{safe}}. (ii) The residual policy satisfies \|\partial \pi_\phi^{\text{res}} / \partial x\| \leq L. (iii) \|d(t)\| \leq D. (iv) Timescale separation \eta \ll 1/\text{control bandwidth}. Then the closed-loop ASI system is ISS:

\|x(t)\| \leq \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma(D)

for some \beta \in \mathcal{KL}, \gamma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty.

Preliminaries.

We consider the Filippov regularized dynamics:

\dot{x} \in \mathbf{F}(x) = \text{co}\{f_i(x, \tau) \mid i \in I(x)\}

where the control input is \tau = \tau_{\text{QP}} + \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}(z, \hat{\theta}).

Lemma A.1 (Lyapunov Function for Nominal QP). Under the QP constraints (3.7)–(3.8), there exists a Lyapunov function V(x) such that for any feasible \tau_{\text{QP}} and any mode i:

\max_{f_i \in \mathbf{F}(x)} \nabla V(x) \cdot f_i(x, \tau_{\text{QP}}) \leq -\alpha V(x) + \gamma_1 \|d(t)\| + \gamma_2 \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\|

where \alpha, \gamma_1, \gamma_2 > 0.

Proof of Lemma A.1. The CLF constraint (3.7) is \dot{V}(x, \tau) \leq -\alpha V(x) + \delta. Because the QP minimizes \delta, we have \delta \leq \delta^* where \delta^* is the minimum relaxation needed for feasibility. From the dynamics (3.1), the actual derivative in mode i is:

\dot{V} = \nabla V \cdot f_i(x, \tau_{\text{QP}} + \pi_\phi^{\text{res}}) + \nabla V \cdot B(x) d(t)

Using the bound \|B(x)\| \leq B_0 and the QP constraint, we obtain the lemma statement. ∎

Lemma A.2 (Bounded Residual Effect). Under timescale separation, \hat{\theta} varies slowly, and \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\| is bounded by a function of the disturbance and adaptation error.

Proof. The residual policy is Lipschitz in state and continuous in \hat{\theta}. Since the slow timescale updates \hat{\theta} with decaying step size, \|\hat{\theta} - \theta^*\| is bounded (by the regret bound, Theorem 3.2). Lipschitz continuity then yields a uniform bound on \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\| over compact sets. ∎

Main Proof.

Define the composite Lyapunov function:

V_c(x, \theta) = V(x) + \frac{\mu}{2} \|\theta - \theta^*\|^2

where \mu > 0 is chosen small enough such that the timescale separation ensures the \theta-dynamics do not destabilize the fast loop.

Taking the upper right Dini derivative along the Filippov inclusion (see Heemels et al., 2008, for the extension to open systems):

D^+ V_c(x(t)) = \max_{f \in \mathbf{F}(x)} \left[ \nabla_x V_c \cdot f + \nabla_\theta V_c \cdot \dot{\theta} \right]

Substituting Lemma A.1 and the adaptation law \dot{\theta} = -\eta \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}:

D^+ V_c \leq -\alpha V(x) + \gamma_1 D + \gamma_2 \|\pi_\phi^{\text{res}}\| - \mu \eta \|\nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}\| \|\theta - \theta^*\|

By Young's inequality and the Lipschitz gradient bound, the cross-term is bounded. Choosing \mu sufficiently small and using Lemma A.2, we obtain:

D^+ V_c \leq -\frac{\alpha}{2} V_c + \Gamma D

for some \Gamma > 0. Applying the comparison lemma for differential inclusions (Filippov, 1988, Thm. 8.1) and the ISS result for discontinuous systems (Heemels et al., 2008, Thm. 1) yields the ISS bound:

V_c(t) \leq e^{-\alpha t/2} V_c(0) + \frac{2\Gamma}{\alpha} D

Since V_c is positive definite and radially unbounded in \|x\|, there exist class \mathcal{K}_\infty functions \underline{\alpha}, \overline{\alpha} such that \underline{\alpha}(\|x\|) \leq V_c(x) \leq \overline{\alpha}(\|x\|). The ISS estimate follows. ∎

