Appendix C: Mathematical Background and Notation

This appendix provides the essential mathematical definitions, theorems, and notation referenced throughout the thesis. It incorporates the enhanced background developed in our session.

C.1 Key Definitions from Hybrid Systems Theory

Definition C.1 (Filippov Differential Inclusion). For a piecewise continuous vector field f: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^n with discontinuity surface \Sigma, the Filippov regularization is:

\mathbf{F}(x) = \bigcap_{\delta > 0} \bigcap_{\mu(N)=0} \overline{\text{co}} \{ f(B(x, \delta) \setminus N) \}

where \overline{\text{co}} denotes closed convex hull, and N is any set of Lebesgue measure zero. This guarantees existence of solutions for rigid-body contact with friction (Filippov, 1988; Brogliato, 2016).

Definition C.2 (Carathéodory Solution). An absolutely continuous function x: [0,T] \to \mathbb{R}^n is a solution if \dot{x}(t) \in \mathbf{F}(x(t)) for almost all t.

Theorem C.1 (ISS for Discontinuous Systems). (Heemels et al., 2008, Thm. 1) For a Filippov system with bounded disturbances, the existence of a piecewise-smooth ISS Lyapunov function V(x) satisfying \max_{f \in \mathbf{F}(x)} \nabla V \cdot f \leq -\alpha V + \gamma(\|d\|) guarantees ISS: \|x(t)\| \leq \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma'(\|d\|_\infty).

C.2 Control Lyapunov and Barrier Functions

Definition C.3 (Control Lyapunov Function – CLF). A continuously differentiable, positive definite, radially unbounded function V: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is a CLF for system \dot{x} = f(x) + g(x)u if there exists a class \mathcal{K} function \alpha such that:

\inf_u \left[ L_f V(x) + L_g V(x) u \right] \leq -\alpha(V(x))

for all x.

Definition C.4 (Control Barrier Function – CBF). For a safe set \mathcal{C} = \{x \mid h(x) \ge 0\}, h is a CBF if there exists an extended class \mathcal{K} function \kappa such that:

\sup_u \left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \kappa(h(x)) \right] \ge 0

for all x \in \mathcal{C} (Ames et al., 2017, 2019).

C.3 Contraction Theory

Definition C.5 (Contraction Metric). A system \dot{x} = f(x,t) is contracting with rate \lambda > 0 in metric M(x) \succ 0 if:

M(x) \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}^\top M(x) + \dot{M}(x) \preceq -2\lambda M(x)

for all x,t (Lohmiller & Slotine, 1998; Tsukamoto et al., 2021).

Theorem C.2 (Contraction implies exponential convergence). If the system is contracting with rate \lambda, then for any two trajectories x(t), y(t):

\|x(t) - y(t)\|_M \leq e^{-\lambda t} \|x(0) - y(0)\|_M

Lemma C.1 (Perturbation of Contraction). (Tsukamoto et al., 2021) If the nominal Jacobian A satisfies \mu_M(A) \leq -\lambda and the perturbation \Delta satisfies \|\Delta\| \leq L, then the matrix measure of A + \Delta satisfies \mu_M(A+\Delta) \leq -\lambda + L.

C.4 PAC-Bayesian Theory

Theorem C.3 (PAC-Bayes Bound for Control). (Hsu et al., 2022) Let P be a prior distribution over policies, Q a posterior, and \ell(\pi, \xi) \in [0,1] a bounded cost. For any \delta \in (0,1), with probability \ge 1-\delta over an i.i.d. sample of size N:

\mathbb{E}_{\pi \sim Q}[R_{\text{real}}(\pi)] \leq \mathbb{E}_{\pi \sim Q}[R_{\text{sim}}(\pi)] + \sqrt{\frac{D_{\text{KL}}(Q \| P) + \log(2\sqrt{N}/\delta)}{2N}}

The structural mismatch term \Delta_{\text{dyn}} accounts for irreducible simulation-to-reality discrepancy.

C.5 Lipschitz Regularization of Neural Networks

Definition C.6 (Spectral Normalization). (Miyato et al., 2018) For a linear layer with weight matrix W, spectral normalization replaces W with W / \|W\|_2, ensuring \|W\|_2 \leq 1. For a ReLU network, the global Lipschitz constant satisfies L \leq \prod_i \|W_i\|_2 \leq 1.

Theorem C.4 (Expected Lipschitz Constant). (Abuduweili et al., 2024) For a randomly initialized MLP with width w and depth d, \mathbb{E}[L] \approx \mathcal{O}(d / \sqrt{w}). This motivates wide, shallow residual networks for ASI to maintain L < \lambda while preserving expressivity.

